<subSubSection pageId="158" pageNumber="761" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="158.[705,1299,1839,2261]" pageId="158" pageNumber="761">
Dasymysfoxi, formerly included in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sundevall" baseAuthorityYear="1847" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Dasymys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="158" pageNumber="761" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="incomtus">D. incomtus</taxonomicName>
, was elevated to full species by M. D. Carleton and C. Martinez in 1991. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[705,1119,2153,2182]" pageId="158" pageNumber="761" type="distribution">
<caption box="[705,1119,2153,2182]" inLine="true" pageId="158" pageNumber="761" startId="158.[705,877,2153,2182]" targetBox="[90,682,1844,2259]" targetPageId="158">
<paragraph blockId="158.[705,1299,1839,2261]" box="[705,1119,2153,2182]" pageId="158" pageNumber="761">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[705,881,2153,2182]" pageId="158" pageNumber="761">Distribution.</emphasis>
C &amp; NE Nigeria.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="158" pageNumber="761" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="158.[705,1299,1839,2261]" lastBlockId="158.[91,1298,2272,2773]" pageId="158" pageNumber="761">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[706,963,2197,2222]" pageId="158" pageNumber="761">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 152 mm, tail 134 mm, ear 21 mm, hindfoot 33 mm; weight 117 g. Like its congeners, Fox’s Shaggy Rat has fur that is soft, shaggy, longhaired, and reddish-brown. Tail is shortish (88% of head-body length).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[93,582,2346,2380]" pageId="158" pageNumber="761" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="158.[91,1298,2272,2773]" box="[93,582,2346,2380]" pageId="158" pageNumber="761">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[93,204,2346,2380]" pageId="158" pageNumber="761">Habitat.</emphasis>
Swampy areas in wetlands.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="158" pageNumber="761" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="158.[91,1298,2272,2773]" pageId="158" pageNumber="761">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[93,353,2385,2419]" pageId="158" pageNumber="761">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
Fox’s Shaggy Rat is predominantly herbivorous. Its diet is presumably similar to that described for the African Shaggy Rat (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sundevall" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[871,1030,2425,2459]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Dasymys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="158" pageNumber="761" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="incomtus">D. incomtus</taxonomicName>
), including aquatic and semi-aquatic plants and insects.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[93,466,2504,2538]" pageId="158" pageNumber="761" type="breeding">
<paragraph blockId="158.[91,1298,2272,2773]" box="[93,466,2504,2538]" pageId="158" pageNumber="761">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[93,227,2504,2538]" pageId="158" pageNumber="761">Breeding.</emphasis>
No information.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="158" pageNumber="761" type="activity">
<paragraph blockId="158.[91,1298,2272,2773]" pageId="158" pageNumber="761">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[91,325,2547,2576]" pageId="158" pageNumber="761">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
Fox’s Shaggy Rats are presumably crepuscular and diurnal, like other members of genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
